    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>root rot? i'm not sure if that's it since the soil feels pretty dry though. it's more like the nutrients are just gone. i read somewhere that yellowing on the bottom leaves might be nitrogen deficiency. how would i check if it's actually nitrogen and what should i do to the ph to help it absorb better?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing of the bottom leaves, especially on tomato plants, can often indicate a nutrient deficiency, such as nitrogen deficiency, which is more concentrated in the lower parts of the plants as they are closer to the soil. \n\nTo check for a nitrogen deficiency, observe the overall appearance of the plant, including leaf discoloration: yellowing starts on the older leaves and progresses toward the younger leaves centrally along the veins. Additionally, consider soil testing to get a precise reading of the nutrient content. Look for the Phosphorus (P) and Potassium (K) levels, as an imbalance may also lead to similar symptoms.\n\nFor improving nutrient uptake, the pH level of the soil is vital. Tomato plants thrive in slightly acidic soil with a pH level between 6.0 and 6.8. To correct the soil pH:\n\n1. Test your soil pH using a simple at-home test kit or a digital pH meter.\n2. If the soil is too acidic (low pH), you can add garden lime to raise it, following the recommended rate on your soil testing kit or label instructions.\n3. If the soil is too alkaline (high pH), add sulfur or aluminum sulfate to lower it, again adhering to",
