    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if it is nitrogen, is that like something that just disappears over time? it feels like it's being stolen or something because the soil looks fine but the plants are starving. is there anything else that might be \"eating\" or depleting the nutrients before the plant can even get to them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, nitrogen can be \"consumed\" in the soil. While plants continuously take up nitrogen, soil microbes and chemical reactions can deplete it. In an active garden, the applied nitrogen compounds can be quickly taken up by the plants, depleted by microbial activity or lost through leaching (moving down from the root zone due to watering). For tomato plants, it's challenging to calculate how much nitrogen is exactly \"eating\" it because it's a dynamic environment. But soil microbes, especially bacteria like Rhizobia which ties nitrogen into actionable forms, might also use some. To prevent this, ensuring a consistent supply of nitrogen through mulching, compost, or nitrogen-fixing plants could help to maintain an adequate level for your tomatoes. If your soil feels dry but still lacks nutrients, you might start with a balanced organic slow-release fertilizer that supplies nitrogen as well as other essential nutrients your plants need. Monitoring your soil and plants regularly can alleviate such issues by adjusting your gardening practices as needed.",
